questiontext.text:
Modelling electrical circuits

Another application of first-order differential equations arises in the modelling of electrical circuits. In Section Modelling with Differential Equations he differential equation for the RL circuit in figure below was shown to be:

\(\qquad L\ \dfrac{di}{dt} + Ri = E\)

in which the initial condition is \(i=0\) at \(t=0\).

First we write this equation in standard form \( \{ \dfrac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)\}\) and obtain the integrating factor.

Dividing the differential equation through by \(L\) gives

\(\qquad \dfrac{di}{dt} + \dfrac{R}{L}\ i = \dfrac{E}{L}\)

which is now in standard form. The integrating factor is \( \text{e}^{\int {R\over L}dt} = \text{e}^{Rt/L}.\)

Multiplying the equation in standard form by the integrating factor gives

\(\qquad \text{e}^{Rt/L} \dfrac{di}{dt} + \text{e}^{Rt/L} \dfrac{R}{L}i = \dfrac{E}{L} \text{e}^{Rt/L}\)

or, rearranging,

\(\qquad \dfrac{d}{dt} (\text{e}^{Rt/L}\ i) = \dfrac{E}{L} \text{e}^{Rt/L}.\)

Now we integrate both sides and apply the initial condition to obtain the solution.

Integrating the differential equation gives:

\(\qquad \text{e}^{Rt/L}\ i = \dfrac{E}{R} \ \text{e}^{Rt/L} + C\)

where \(C\) is a constant so

\(\qquad i = \dfrac{E}{R} + C e^{-Rt/L}\)

Applying the initial condition \(i=0\) when \(t=0\) gives

\( \qquad 0 = \dfrac{E}{R} + C\)

so that \(C = -\dfrac{E}{R}.\)

Finally, \(\, i=\dfrac{E}{R}(1-\text{e}^{-Rt/L}).\)

Note that as \(t\to \infty, \, i\to \dfrac{E}{R}\) so as \(t\) increases the effect of the inductor diminishes to zero.
